<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-152-003 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 957 960</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  May 20 1991 v8 n10 p87(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bridge performance test methodology. (used in evaluations of nineEthernet bridges)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Germann, Christopher; Bowden, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The test suite used by the LAN TIMES laboratory in the evaluationof nine Ethernet local bridges comprised three timed tests thatdetermined the devices application isolation capabilities,forwarding rate, and latency.andP;  The application isolation test wasdesigned to prove that MAC- (media access control-) layer bridgesimprove network performance by reducing unnecessary traffic.andP;  Itshould be noted that the actual performance improvement yielded isnominal.andP;  This test was weighted as 65 percent of the totalperformance score.andP;  Forwarding rates were established by firingone-second bursts of packets, increasing the gap between packetsin 10-microsecond increments until the point at which 100 percentof the packets were being forwarded was reached.andP;  Latency, whichis the term that describes how a bridge affects the speed of apacket from node to node, was determined using a NovellLananalyzer to monitor interpacket delays.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Bridges (Connector)TestingPerformance Measurement.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Application isolation test. (graph)Forwarding rates. (graph)Bridge latency. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>